This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with stereo cameras and dense stereo matching algorithms. It also involves the use of natural features and optimization techniques to obtain high-precision stereo extrinsic calibration. 

It could also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as stereo cameras and dense depth measurements are core components for many robotic applications. 

The paper's use of optimization techniques and machine learning principles to improve stereo extrinsic calibration could also place it in the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper's focus on improving the reliability of stereo vision systems for long-term autonomy could place it in the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category, which deals with computer graphics and visualization techniques for real-world applications.
